    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <opener><dateline><placeName ref="pl0001">Downing</placeName> Dec<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> 26<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1777</dateline>
                <salute> Dear Sir</salute></opener>
                <p>accept the best wishes of the season with my thanks for y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> last favour. I quite approve of <persName ref="pe0156">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Low’s</persName> reasonable delay of visiting
                    the rest of <placeName ref="pl0701">the orknies</placeName>. He had best reserve
                    it for the good season &amp; good company. in less than a fortnight I shall
                    begin to read his <bibl type="authorial"><title ref="bi0058">M.S.S.</title></bibl> let me beg you would on no account communicate his
                        <rs ref="ar0204">drawings</rs> which would be a most cruel anticipation. I
                    beg to know if <persName ref="pe0159">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                        Mackenzie</persName> published charts of the <placeName ref="pl0700">Shetlands</placeName> if he has <persName ref="pe0156">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Low</persName> should take the benefit of
                    them. I inclose those of <placeName ref="pl0701">the orknies</placeName> taken
                    from <bibl type="authorial"><title ref="bi0209">my map</title></bibl> borrowed
                    from <bibl type="authorial"><title ref="bi0098">Mackenzie</title></bibl> for
                        <persName ref="pe0156">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Low</persName> to
                        see.<note type="editorial">Pennant is describing those sections of his own
                            <bibl type="editorial"><title ref="bi0209"><hi rend="italic">Map of
                                    Scotland</hi></title></bibl> that had been traced from Murdoch
                        MacKenzie's charts of the <bibl type="editorial"><title ref="bi0098"><hi rend="italic">Orkney Islands</hi></title></bibl> (1750): see
                        Pennant's letter to Paton on 27 August 1776.</note> I am heartily sorry that
                    <persName ref="pe0022">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Ramsay</persName> has that
                    torturing disorder the rheumatism: but sincerely wish his speedy recovery. I
                    wonder what is become of <persName ref="pe0104">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                        Gough</persName> who has been long silent.</p>
                <closer><salute>I am Dear Sir <lb/>Y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> affect. humble
                            Serv<hi rend="superscript">t</hi></salute>
                    <signed><persName ref="pe0232">Tho. Pennant.</persName></signed></closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>my munificent friend <persName ref="pe0056">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                        Constable</persName> of <placeName ref="pl0031">Burton Constable</placeName>
                        <placeName ref="pl0770">yorkshire</placeName> has given 6 guineas to be laid in
                            <gap reason="illegible" unit="words" quantity="1"/> or print for
                        <persName ref="pe0156">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Low’s</persName>
                        <bibl type="authorial"><title ref="bi0058">voyage</title></bibl>.</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
